04402nmm a2200589Ia 9780801460777DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20112015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979630437  a97808014607777 a10.7591/97808014607772doi  a(DE-B1597)478350  a(OCoLC)742515532  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a324.65223  aMF 4000qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122712:1 aHyde, Susan D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Pseudo-Democrat's Dilemma :bWhy Election Observation Became an International Norm /cSusan D. Hyde. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b2 halftones, 1 map, 18 tables, 17 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy did election monitoring become an international norm? Why do pseudo-democrats—undemocratic leaders who present themselves as democratic—invite international observers, even when they are likely to be caught manipulating elections? Is election observation an effective tool of democracy promotion, or is it simply a way to legitimize electoral autocracies? In The Pseudo-Democrat’s Dilemma, Susan D. Hyde explains international election monitoring with a new theory of international norm formation. Hyde argues that election observation was initiated by states seeking international support. International benefits tied to democracy give some governments an incentive to signal their commitment to democratization without having to give up power. Invitations to nonpartisan foreigners to monitor elections, and avoiding their criticism, became a widely recognized and imitated signal of a government’s purported commitment to democratic elections.Hyde draws on cross-national data on the global spread of election observation between 1960 and 2006, detailed descriptions of the characteristics of countries that do and do not invite observers, and evidence of three ways that election monitoring is costly to pseudo-democrats: micro-level experimental tests from elections in Armenia and Indonesia showing that observers can deter election-day fraud and otherwise improve the quality of elections; illustrative cases demonstrating that international benefits are contingent on democracy in countries like Haiti, Peru, Togo, and Zimbabwe; and qualitative evidence documenting the escalating game of strategic manipulation among pseudo-democrats, international monitors, and pro-democracy forces.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocratization. 0aElection monitoring. 0aElectionsxCorrupt practices. 0aInternational relations. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  ainternational election observation, election interference, development of norms, international affairs, election fraud.2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801460777?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460777423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801460777/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles